{"metadata":{"kernelspec":{"name":"ir","display_name":"R","language":"R"},"language_info":{"name":"R","codemirror_mode":"r","pygments_lexer":"r","mimetype":"text/x-r-source","file_extension":".r","version":"4.0.5"},"kaggle":{"accelerator":"none","dataSources":[{"sourceId":8602116,"sourceType":"datasetVersion","datasetId":5146801}],"dockerImageVersionId":30618,"isInternetEnabled":true,"language":"r","sourceType":"notebook","isGpuEnabled":false}},"nbformat_minor":4,"nbformat":4,"cells":[{"source":"<a href=\"https://www.kaggle.com/code/alvinhanafie/can-we-predict-car-prices-from-its-power-in-r?scriptVersionId=181428348\" target=\"_blank\"><img align=\"left\" alt=\"Kaggle\" title=\"Open in Kaggle\" src=\"https://kaggle.com/static/images/open-in-kaggle.svg\"></a>","metadata":{},"cell_type":"markdown"},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Dataset Overview for Car Price Prediction","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## Let's explore how Car Horsepower affects Car Price!","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# We will use linear regression to model the relationship between car price and car horsepower.\n\n# Import Library\nlibrary(ggplot2) # for plotting\nlibrary(caTools) # for train-test data split\n\n# Import Data\ndf <- read.csv(\"/kaggle/input/car-prices-based-on-horsepower/mobil_mesin_harga.csv\")\n\n# Change column name of KekuatanMesin and Harga\nnames(df)[c(1, 2)] <- c(\"Car_Horsepower\", \"Car_Price\")\n\n# What insights can we glean from the summary statistics?\n# Are there any missing values or outliers we should address?\nsummary(df)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2024-06-04T11:06:29.005111Z","iopub.execute_input":"2024-06-04T11:06:29.00776Z","iopub.status.idle":"2024-06-04T11:06:29.056098Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"- No missing value found in the dataset. If there are any NA value, it will be showed in the summary. \n- Mean of Car_Horsepower is slightly higher than its median.\n- The maximum value of Car Horsepower is extremely higher than its 3rd Quartile. We will handle this outlier later. \n- Let's take a closer look at the data using visualization. ","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# We will create histograms to have better visualization of car price and car horsepower distribution\nhist(df$Car_Horsepower, main = \"Car Horsepower Distribution\", xlab = \"Horsepower\", col = \"skyblue\")\nhist(df$Car_Price, main = \"Car Price Distribution\", xlab = \"Price\", col = \"lightgreen\")","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2024-06-04T11:06:29.059488Z","iopub.execute_input":"2024-06-04T11:06:29.061208Z","iopub.status.idle":"2024-06-04T11:06:29.246319Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"- The data distribution of Car Horsepower is centered around 50 - 150.\n- The data distribution of Car Price is centered below 200.\n- Data distribution for both Car Price and Car Horsepower are positively-skewed.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# We will visualize the relationship using a scatterplot.\n\nggplot(df, aes(x = Car_Horsepower, y = Car_Price)) +\n  geom_point() +\n  labs(title = \"Car Price vs. Car Horsepower\", \n       x = \"Car_Horsepower\", y = \"Car_Price\")\n\n# Since the feature is only one, we do not need to scale the data.\n\n# Below are codes if the data is scaled\n# df$Car_Horsepower <- scale(df$Car_Horsepower)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2024-06-04T11:06:29.249499Z","iopub.execute_input":"2024-06-04T11:06:29.251132Z","iopub.status.idle":"2024-06-04T11:06:29.515505Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Outlier Handling","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Let's handle outliers using a method called 'interquartile range' (IQR). \n\nThe IQR basically tells us the spread of the middle half of the data. We can then calculate upper and lower limits based on the IQR. Data points that fall significantly above the upper limit or below the lower limit are considered outliers. ","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Determine outlier boundaries by IQR method\nfind_outlier_boundary <- function(data, variable) {\n  IQR <- IQR(data[, variable])  # Calculate IQR using IQR function\n  lower_boundary <- quantile(data[, variable], 0.25) - (IQR * 1.5)\n  upper_boundary <- quantile(data[, variable], 0.75) + (IQR * 1.5)\n  return(c(upper_boundary, lower_boundary))  # Return upper and lower boundaries\n}\n\n# Determine outlier boundaries for Car_Horsepower\nboundaries <- find_outlier_boundary(df, \"Car_Horsepower\")\nupper_boundary <- boundaries[1]\nlower_boundary <- boundaries[2]\n\n# Replace outliers with upper or lower boundaries\ndf$Car_Horsepower <- ifelse(df$Car_Horsepower > upper_boundary, upper_boundary,\n                            ifelse(df$Car_Horsepower < lower_boundary, lower_boundary, df$Car_Horsepower))\n\n# Summary after outlier handling\nsummary(df$Car_Horsepower)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2024-06-04T11:06:29.518546Z","iopub.execute_input":"2024-06-04T11:06:29.520131Z","iopub.status.idle":"2024-06-04T11:06:29.552364Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"After outlier handling, the maximum value of Car Horsepower has changed from 262.0 to 185.0. ","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Model Training using Linear Regression","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# We will do Linear Regression model training\n\n# We will set seed number (or random state in Python) for result reproducibility\nset.seed(123)\n\n# Train-test data split before create a model for model testing and evaluation\n# Since the dataset is relatively small, we will use 80% of the dataset for model learning\ndf_split = sample.split(df$Car_Price, SplitRatio = 0.8)\n\n# Train set and test set by ratio 0.8\ntrainset = subset(df,df_split==TRUE)\ntestset = subset(df,df_split==FALSE)\n\n# Train the model using linear regression\nlinear_regression <- lm(Car_Price ~ Car_Horsepower, data = trainset)\n\n# Show summary for model training results\nsummary(linear_regression)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2024-06-04T11:06:29.55599Z","iopub.execute_input":"2024-06-04T11:06:29.557667Z","iopub.status.idle":"2024-06-04T11:06:29.598196Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"As we can see from the summary, Car_Horsepower is strong predictor for Car_Price, highlighted by *** in the summary. \n\nThe coefficient for the model is Car_Price = -47.52 + 1.72 * Car_Horsepower.\n\nBased on Linear Regression model: \nEvery 1 increment from Car_Horsepower will increase Car_Price by 1.72","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Right now, we already train our model\n# Let's predict car prices for data test set with our model\n\nCar_Price_Prediction = predict(linear_regression, newdata=testset)\n\n# Create df_merge to merge between actual car price and predicted car price\ndf_merge = cbind(testset, Car_Price_Prediction)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2024-06-04T11:06:29.601459Z","iopub.execute_input":"2024-06-04T11:06:29.603268Z","iopub.status.idle":"2024-06-04T11:06:29.621417Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Car Price vs. Car Horsepower Visualization for Actual and Predicted Values\n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"To have clear visualization to compare the actual car price and prediction car price, we will create a scatterplot.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"ggplot(testset, aes(x = Car_Horsepower, y = Car_Price)) +\n  geom_point(aes(color = \"Actual\"), size = 3) +  # Actual data points\n  geom_point(aes(x = Car_Horsepower, y = Car_Price_Prediction, color = \"Predicted\"), size = 3) + # Predicted data points from test set\n  labs(title = \"Actual vs. Predicted Car Price\",\n       x = \"Car_Horsepower\", y = \"Car_Price\",\n       color = \"Data\") +\n  geom_smooth(aes(x = Car_Horsepower, y = predict(linear_regression, newdata = testset)), \n              method = \"lm\", linetype = \"dashed\", color = \"blue\")","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2024-06-04T11:06:29.624509Z","iopub.execute_input":"2024-06-04T11:06:29.626188Z","iopub.status.idle":"2024-06-04T11:06:30.052783Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"It seems that Car Price prediction using Linear Regression will perform better in predicting car price with low car horsepower. As the car price goes higher, the prediction become less accurate.\n\nIs this model good enough? \n\nLet's evaluate the model performance using MAE and RMSE metrics.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Model Evaluation using Mean Absolute Error (MAE) and Root Mean Square Error (RMSE)","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Mean Absolute Error\nmae <- mean(abs(df_merge$Car_Price_Prediction - df_merge$Car_Price))\nprint(paste(\"Mean Absolute Error (MAE):\", mae))","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2024-06-04T11:06:30.055807Z","iopub.execute_input":"2024-06-04T11:06:30.057394Z","iopub.status.idle":"2024-06-04T11:06:30.074662Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"MAE = 32.48.\n\nThis means that the model have average deviation from the true value by 32.48.\n\nSince the range of car prices between minimum and maximum is 402.82, the MAE value from model is relatively low.\n\nThis information indicated that the model already performed well at car price prediction.\n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Root Mean Square Error\nrmse <- sqrt(mean((df_merge$Car_Price_Prediction - df_merge$Car_Price) ** 2))\nprint(paste(\"Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE):\", rmse))","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2024-06-04T11:06:30.077589Z","iopub.execute_input":"2024-06-04T11:06:30.079209Z","iopub.status.idle":"2024-06-04T11:06:30.096964Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"RMSE = 52.23.\n\nThis means that the model have average deviation from the true value by 52.23.\n\nSince the range of car prices between minimum and maximum is 402.82, the RMSE value from model is relatively low.\n\nThis information indicated that the model already performed well at car price prediction.\n\nSince the difference of MAE and RMSE is not high, the model is relatively robust to outliers. \n\nRMSE value is higher than MAE because it multiply the errors, especially in higher prices in the dataset that may be classified as outlier, between actual and predicted data.\n\nBoth MAE and RMSE are in relatively low, which means the errors from model is not large. ","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"I am just getting started with R, so any feedbacks and suggestions would be a lifesaver!\n\nThank you!","metadata":{}}]}